<ul>
<li>Cardiogenic shock is defined as a sustained (&gt;30 minutes) episode of systolic&nbsp;blood pressure &lt;90 mm Hg, and/or cardiac index &lt;2.2 L/min/m2 determined to&nbsp;be secondary to cardiac dysfunction, and/or the requirement for parenteral&nbsp;inotropic or vasopressor agents or mechanical support (e.g., IABP,&nbsp;extracorporeal circulation, ventricular assist devices) to maintain bloodpressure and cardiac index above those specified levels.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Source: ACC Data Standards</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<ul>
<li>Transient episodes of hypotension reversed with IV fluid or atropine do not&nbsp;constitute cardiogenic shock. The hemodynamic compromise (with or&nbsp;without extraordinary supportive therapy) must persist for at least 30&nbsp;minutes</li>
<li>For patients with extended hospital stays, restrict coding of post-procedure events to 30 days after the last procedure.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'CathPCI Registry v4.4', NULL, 'Cardiogenic Shock', ' PostCardiogenicShock', NULL, NULL, NULL, ' User', 707, '2016-09-14 15:57:00', '2018-01-07 07:34:09', NULL);
