<ul>
<li>Cumulative air kerma (also known as reference, reference dose, cumulative dose, or cumulative dose at a reference point) is the air kerma accumulated at a specific point in space (the patient entrance reference point) relative to the gantry of the fluoroscopy system.</li>
<li>The quantity, kerma, originated from the acronym, KERMA, for Kinetic Energy Released per unit MAss (of air).</li>
<li><strong><span style="background-color: #ffff00;">Source: Miller DL, Balter S, Cole PE, et al. Radiation doses in interventional radiology procedures: the RAD-IR study. I. Overall measures of dose. J Vasc Interv Radiol 2003; 14:711&acirc;727.</span></strong></li>
<li>&nbsp;</li>
</ul>', '<p>Please collect Fluoroscopy Time, Cumulative Air Kerma and Dose Area Product values, if available. If biplane equipment is used, collect the total dose of both planes and add them together.</p>', NULL, NULL, 'Fluoroscopy Dose - Cumulative Air Kerma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 716, '2016-09-14 15:57:00', '2018-06-08 02:12:10', NULL);
